  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research on the permanent deconstruction of intracellular primary cilia in differentiating granule cell neurons has made a significant academic impact, accumulating 24 citations since its preprint release on bioRxiv. This work reflects a strong institutional foundation, notably involving key contributors from Harvard University and The University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"Permanent deconstruction of intracellular primary cilia in differentiating granule cell neurons\" has garnered notable attention within the academic community, with 24 citations indicating its influence and relevance in the field. This study, which has successfully transitioned to a peer-reviewed publication in the Journal of Cell Biology, demonstrates the authors' commitment to open science, facilitating immediate community engagement and scholarly discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research showcases significant contributions from esteemed institutions, including Harvard University and The University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center, highlighting a strong collaborative effort that enhances the credibility and reach of the findings. This collaboration underscores the interconnected nature of modern scientific inquiry and the collective drive toward advancing knowledge in cellular biology.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the lack of public discourse on social platforms like Reddit or Wikipedia, the academic citations indicate a solid uptake in scholarly discussions. The significant number of citations since both its preprint and subsequent peer-reviewed publication illustrates the work\u2019s importance in shaping ongoing research themes concerning primary cilia and neuronal differentiation.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the researchers' commitment to sharing early findings before formal publication has allowed for timely knowledge dissemination within the community. This approach not only enriches the discourse but also promotes the transparent evolution of scientific understanding, illustrating the importance of preprints in the lifecycle of research publications.</p>",
